{"cursor":"49320","size":15,"audio":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/45/Firetruck.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b2/Whelen.ogg"],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n, England, responding to an emergency call, 2010]] A 'fire apparatus', 'fire\nengine', 'fire truck', or 'fire appliance' is a vehicle designed to assist in\nfighting fires by transporting firefighters to the scene and providing them with\naccess to the fire, along with water or other equipment. In some areas, the\nterms fire engine and fire truck represent different types of firefighting\napparatus.\n\nA modern fire engine is usually a multi-purpose vehicle carrying paid\nfirefighters or volunteers and equipment for a wide range of firefighting and\nrescue tasks. Therefore, most fire engines carry equipment such as ladders, pike\npoles, axes and cutting equipment, halligan bars, fire extinguishers,\nventilating equipment, floodlights, hose ramps, self-contained breathing\napparatus (SCBA), and general tools. Many fire appliances are based on standard\ntruck or lorry models with heavy duty suspensions, brakes, tires, alternator,\ntransmission and cooling systems; audible and visual warnings such as sirens,\nhorns, and flashing lights; and a two-way radio.\n\nThe fire engine may have several methods of pumping water onto the fire, such as\npassing water obtained from a fire hydrant through hoses or using a pumping\n\"cannon\" (also known as a monitor or deck gun); some trucks have an onboard\nwater reservoir. Some fire engines may carry ladders to gain access to fires\noccurring in high-rise buildings and remove casualties, or hooks used to pull\nwalls away to expose hidden fire or break windows. In some regions, a 'rescue\nunit' is an EMS truck with tools to carry out technical rescues of people from\ntraffic collisions or structural collapses.\n\nFire departments covering large metropolitan areas may have specialist\nappliances for dealing with hazardous material incidents. Some fire departments\nmay utilise fire trains, fireboats or airplanes, depending on the local\ngeography.\n","linknr":633,"url":"Fire_apparatus","recorded":1362579671,"links":72,"instances":["railway","builder","fire_apparatus","railway","noisemaker"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Fire service vehicles","Trucks","Firefighting"],"headings":["Types","Other functions","Design and construction","Crew assignment","History","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Cambridgeshire_fire_engine.jpg/220px-Cambridgeshire_fire_engine.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/NSW_Fire_Brigades_Pumper_Class_2_and_rescue.jpg/220px-NSW_Fire_Brigades_Pumper_Class_2_and_rescue.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Firefighting_ladder_trucks.jpg/220px-Firefighting_ladder_trucks.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/Lafd_ladder_truck.jpg/220px-Lafd_ladder_truck.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Roskilde_S1.jpg/220px-Roskilde_S1.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Sapporo_Fire_bureau_odori_2_A-2class_TypeII.jpg/220px-Sapporo_Fire_bureau_odori_2_A-2class_TypeII.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/Brush_28_of_PBCFR.jpg/220px-Brush_28_of_PBCFR.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.2